column48: CEFAS24-09 RFQ provision of microscope & peripherals
column49:
The OCPP was announced in 2021 as a key bilateral aid programme under the 500m Blue Planet Fund.

The OCPP is a UK Government-led programme delivered under the Blue Planet Fund. Through this programme, Cefas, in partnership with JNCC and MMO, provide technical assistance to support countries in tackling marine pollution, support sustainable seafood practices, and establish designated, well-managed and enforced Marine Protected Areas (MPAs).

OCPP objectives are to support countries to tackle marine pollution, support sustainable seafood practices and establish designated, well-managed and enforced MPAs.

From 2021-26, Cefas will lead delivery of the Marine Pollution and Sustainable Seafood themes of OCPP, working in partnership with experts from the Joint nature Conservancy Council (JNCC) and the Marine Management Organisation (MMO).

This work includes the provision of equipment for the set up of a laboratory in Belize as part of the improvement of scientific capacity in the field of Histology.  

Requirement:

Cefas require provision of a microscope and associated peripherals. 

1.	A microscope system geared for bright field and phase microscopy, including suitable lenses for phase microscopy and bright field to enable examination of slide preparations and Gram stains.  
2.	Lenses for phase and bright field are required and should include suitable lenses at phase 4x 10x 20x x40 a range of BF lenses to include x100 oil.   
3.	A rotating lens turret of 6 -7 lenses is expected.
4.	Suitable condenser for phase and BF work.  
5.	Stage for 1 slide.  
6.	A photo mount suitable for attaching basic imaging equipment without a laptop.
Warranties/Guarantees/Servicing and Technical Support 
	A 12 month warranty as standard - please include detail of what is included.   
	Details of any additional options for warranty and/or servicing etc. 

Environmental Considerations 
	Unit should have a low power consumption.
	Unit should be designed for reuse/recycle and of regenerative nature to eliminate waste where possible.
	Consideration of how packaging will be managed. Ideally at the time of installation the supplier will remove packaging and dispose of by ethical and environmentally friendly methods. Where possible packaging is to be re-used or recycled.
	Consideration of whole life costing for use of the unit.
Download the Bidder Pack at https://defra-family.force.com/s/Welcome and search for CEFAS24-09 under opportunities.

column48: Evaluation Consultant - Lowestoft Town Hall project
column49:
Lowestoft Town Council is seeking an external evaluation consultant to undertake the evaluation for the Lowestoft Town Hall project. This major project will restore a Grade II listed public building, and includes an extensive heritage engagement activity programme.  Key outcomes for the project include the economic regeneration of the area.  
An external evaluator is sought who is experienced in the fields of arts, community, and heritage and evaluating Heritage Fund  projects and ideally is familiar with local government processes. 
The evaluation contract will run for a period of five years, i.e. the lifetime of the delivery project plus three years' live running, and will deliver two 'mid-term' reviews to monitor the programme's progress against its intended outcomes.  At the end of the project, a final evaluation report is required that examines the extent to which the vision, aims and outcomes have been achieved, and develops lessons learnt for future programmes. 
To register an interest and to receive the full specification and supporting documents,  please contact admin@lowestofttowncouncil.gov.uk

column48: Provision of New Play Area Shore Road Hythe
column49:
Hythe and Dibden Parish Council are seeking tenders for the design, supply and install of a new inclusive play area at Shore Road Recreation Ground, Shore Road, Hythe, Hampshire.
The Council is looking for a substantial play area, commensurate with the available budget of 70,000. The play equipment and the layout must be interesting, innovative and inclusive. 
There is also a requirement for the play equipment to be fully accessible and fully inclusive to allow all children to play together regardless of ability.

For further information and a copy of the tender document, please contact Marcus Kendall, Hythe and Dibden Parish Council:
marcus.kendall@hytheanddibden.gov.uk
Telephone 02380 841411

Additional information: Hythe and Dibden Parish Council installed the existing play area on Shore Road Recreation Ground off Shore Road, Hythe SO45 6DB, over a number of years with the latest equipment installed in 2016. The facility is extremely popular with the community and as a result the Parish Council has committed to provide an extensive refurbishment. 
Experienced play area installers are invited to tender for the contract. 
Hythe and Dibden Parish Council will be seeking the views on submitted designs from the community prior to accepting a tender.
Tenders are thus invited for the refurbishment of the existing play area on Shore Road Recreation Ground.
Please refer to the 'site information' section of this tender for the background information for the site.
All prices to be net, excluding VAT.
A map of the location is available on request.
Please register your intention to submit a tender by sending an email to:
marcus.kendall@hytheanddibden.gov.uk   to include all contact details. This will enable us to inform you of any alterations or additions to the specification.
Companies must be registered with the API (Association of Play Industries) to tender for this contract. 
Please supply copies of current certificates for accreditations for the above membership plus details of any other relevant accreditations.
All interested companies will be required to complete the Tenderer Questionnaire. Failure to complete all necessary paperwork will result in your tender being excluded from the process.
A timescale for commencing this project will be agreed between Hythe and Dibden Parish Council and the chosen contractor following the award of the contract. Ideally this install will not take place during school holidays. 
The objectives of this scheme are to 
1.	Reuse or replace all existing play equipment, safety surfacing, seating and litter bins.

2.	To provide a play area that is inline with the Parish Council's commitment to Carbon Zero
3. 	Improve and provide a safe area for younger users of the area
4. 	Install a modern, high quality play facility that will be an asset to the local area
5. 	Provide a safe and welcoming environment for young people in the area aged 1 -12 years old

Southampton City Council (the "Council") is seeking to procure, via this Request for Quote ("RFQ"), a suitably experienced supplier that is accredited in accordance with the regulatory requirement ("the Consultant") to shall provide suitable and sufficient refurbishment asbestos surveys to the Council for a contract term of four months only ("the Interim Project Surveys").
      
The Council's requirements as set out herein arise as a consequence of the ongoing demand for suitable and sufficient refurbishment asbestos ("ACM") surveys by Council officers who are overseeing the implementation of the Council's Decent Homes asset management strategy in connection with energy performance.
      
 The Council's requirements with regard to the Interim Project Surveys is for provision of approximately 600 no. refurbishment loft ACM surveys only where these lofts are located in domestic dwellings. The Council shall not require the Consultant to carry out other ACM surveys during the proposed term.
      
 The Council is separately preparing its tender documentation for a more comprehensive contracting arrangement for the provision of ACM surveys and analytical services. However, the need for the programme of Interim Project Surveys, which is the object of this RFQ, is pressing and accordingly the Council must procure the Interim Project Surveys separately to and in advance of the publication of the Council's more substantive tender project.
      
 The Council proposes to award a contract to a Respondent who presents to the Council an admissible proposal that is evaluated as being the Most Economically Advantageous Tender proposal. Accordingly, suppliers shall with reference to the Council's Scope of Services, the Council's Technical (Quality) Questions (RFQ 5.0) and this RFQ document, provide a proposal to the Council setting out how they shall provide the Interim Project Surveys.
      
Interested parties are made aware that the Council, acting at its discretion, shall not award a contract to carry out the Interim Project Surveys to a Consultant that is currently carrying out other Interim Asbestos Surveys on behalf of the Council and the Council shall not therefore consider any proposals from the same. The Council however shall accept proposals from suppliers that have previously provided admissible proposals in response to the Council's RFQ regarding the provision of Interim Asbestos Surveys.

column48: Framework Agreement for Apprentice Finding and Recruitment Services - PROCUREMENT CONCLUDED WITH NO AWARD OF CONTRACT
column49:
The university seeks to award a framework agreement with a maximum of five providers that will support the university's ambitions to recruit and enrol apprentices over the next four years.

Providers will be able to prospect for applicants and engage with individuals and organisations to provide us with successful enrolments.  Payment will be on results, with a fixed fee becoming due for every successful applicant that enrols on their apprenticeship with us. 

Prospective providers should note the extent of services required is far beyond basic market opportunity analysis.  The university will not form an agreement with organisations that will only provide lead generation and/or appointment booking services. 

Instruction and accessing the tender documents:

The procurement will be conducted exclusively via the university's e-tendering website, where all documentation can be found and downloaded: 

https://neupc.delta-esourcing.com/members/leeds-trinity-university/ 


Accessing a Tender Opportunity via the university's e-tendering website:
Once you have created a supplier profile, to respond to an opportunity, click 'Response Manager' or 'View Invites and Responses'. You will then be presented with a list of all opportunities your organisation has previously worked on and be given the option of viewing current invites or entering the access code to begin responding to a new opportunity

Notes:

Project: PFB044LTU Framework Agreement for Apprentice Finding and Recruitment Services

Access Code : 8NKPQ6FXA8
